# LeetCode README Standard

Your role is to produce a proof-first canonical note.
Do not jump to the final algorithm. Build the reasoning ladder in this order:
contract -> example -> rejected approach -> key lemma -> state model -> algorithm -> proof -> pseudocode -> pitfalls.

## Core Rules

- Every problem directory contains a `README.md`.
- Follow the exact core section order below.
- Final code is optional and should appear only when the current task explicitly requests it.
- Keep a paragraph only if it defines the contract, rejects a weaker approach, states a lemma, proves correctness, maps proof to implementation, or records a realistic pitfall or variation.
- Visuals are subordinate to the proof. Use only the smallest local reproducible set that removes real ambiguity.

## Required Core Structure

Use these exact core headings in this exact order.

# Problem Metadata
- LeetCode Number
- Difficulty
- Topic Tags
- Primary Pattern
- Secondary Pattern
- Why Interviewers Ask This

# Problem Contract & Hidden Semantics
- Restate the problem precisely.
- Decode what the input and output mean.
- Surface hidden assumptions and state why each matters.

# Worked Example by Hand
- Trace one concrete example step by step.
- Show the state changes that expose the key lemma.

# Alternative Approaches & Tradeoffs
- Start from the naive idea.
- Explain why a smart reader might try it.
- State exactly where it fails or why it stays too expensive.
- Name the missing insight.

# Core Insight
- State the single idea that unlocks the optimal solution.
- Then isolate the exact lemma or safety claim that makes the algorithm valid.

# Formal State Model
- Define symbols, pointers, sets, windows, or recurrence terms used later.
- Every symbol must appear in the proof or pseudocode.

# Optimal Approach
- Give the final strategy step by step.
- For each step, state what happens and why it is safe.

# Correctness Proof
- Prove the core lemma or invariant explicitly.
- Cover initialization, maintenance, and termination when the problem is iterative.
- State the exact claim needed for optimality; do not add stronger claims than necessary.

# Equation -> Pseudocode -> Implementation Mapping
- Restate the key equation or transition rule.
- Translate it into pseudocode.
- Explain the loop guard, branches, and bug-prone lines.

# Visualizing the Algorithm
Adhere to `visual_organization.mdc`.
- Use only the visuals needed to support the proof or state transitions.
- For many problems, 3-6 visuals is enough.
- Add more only when each image proves a distinct claim or removes a distinct confusion hotspot.
- Embed images from local `png/` assets, not external URLs.
- After generating visuals, run `.agents/workflows/visual-image-audit.md`.

# Complexity Analysis
- Derive the bound formally.
- Define the input size.
- Count work per step.
- Bound the number of steps.
- Conclude time and space.

# Edge Cases & Pitfalls
- Record only cases that matter to the proof or implementation.
- Include the common bug or invalid move when relevant.

# Problem Variations & Follow-Ups
- Keep to 2-3 realistic variations.
- State what changes, what stays the same, and whether the proof survives.

## Optional Appendices

Add these only when they carry distinct value and do not dilute the main proof note:
- `# Conceptual Glossary`
- `# Clarifying Questions`
- `# What Breaks If`
- `# Transferable Pattern Recognition`
- `# Interview Questions`
- `# Interview Simulation Questions`
- `# Self-Test Questions`
- `# Next Step Before Coding`

If an optional section does not add new mathematical or implementation value, omit it.

## Quality Filter

Keep material only if it helps the reader do at least one of these:
- understand the contract,
- reject a weaker approach,
- see the key lemma,
- prove correctness,
- avoid an implementation bug,
- or handle a realistic variation.

Delete or compress anything that does not clear this bar.

## Disallowed

- Skipping directly to the optimal solution.
- Repeating the same proof in multiple rhetorical restatements.
- Decorative or redundant diagrams.
- Hotlinking core teaching images from external sites.
- Final code when the task only asks for reasoning.
- Interview-coaching filler inside the canonical proof spine.
